{{About|a region in Arizona|a region with the same name in China|Guanggu (disambiguation){{!}}Guanggu}} [[Image:LargeBinoTelescope_NASA.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Large Binocular Telescope]] on [[Mount Graham]], east of Tucson]]'''Optics Valley''' is a region in southern [[Arizona]], centered on [[Tucson]], that is home to a high concentration of [[optics]] companies spawned by research at the [[University of Arizona]].<ref>{{cite book | title = Insiders' Guide to Tucson | author = Mary Paganelli Votto | publisher = Globe Pequot | year = 2006 | ISBN = 0-7627-4193-7 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=29zWkAeTueAC&pg=PA10&dq=%22optics+valley%22+%22university+of+arizona%22&lr=&as_brr=3&ei=pclASN_WHoLGjgG89NCJBQ&sig=2vpt0uEZRFxjxYoC25c5SfEoUFc }}</ref> Based on the idea of a technology cluster such as [[Silicon Valley]], Optics Valley is known not only for its optics industry and research but also for the [[astronomical observatories]] located in the mountains of southern Arizona where clear skies and isolated peaks make for superior observing conditions.<ref>{{cite book | title = A Visitor's Guide to the Kitt Peak Observatories | author = Leslie Sage and Gail Aschenbrenner | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2004 | ISBN = 0-521-00652-X | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=wcuhhpE4-_wC&pg=PA79&dq=tucson+kitt-peak+mount-graham+university+arizona&lr=&as_brr=3&ei=rMpASLjvDoegiwHJktSIBQ&sig=yjrxWMhvtRRRyTxdXL6bVJreKSc }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Banking on Optics Valley: The Old Pueblo has high hopes for high tech, but little time | author = D. A. Barber | work = Tucson Weekly | url = http://www.tucsonweekly.com/gbase/Currents/Content?oid=43473 | date = January 4, 2001}}</ref>
